revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}
{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}
'''BBC Redux''' is a [[BBC Research & Development]] system that digitally records<ref name="solon"/> [[digital terrestrial television in the United Kingdom|television and radio output in the United Kingdom]] produced by the [[British Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|2}}  It has been operating since 2007<ref name="solon"/> and contains several [[petabyte]]s of recordings<ref name="solon"/> and subtitle data.<ref name="solon">{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2011-06/16/bbc-research-and-development?page=all|title=The people and projects inside the BBC's vast R&D lab|first=Olivia|last=Solon|work=Wired|date=16 June 2011|accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>  It is notable for being the [[proof of concept]] for the [[Flash video]] streaming version of the [[BBC iPlayer]].<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|15}}

It is an internal research project developed for testing<ref name="butterworth"/><ref name="saran">{{cite news|url=http://www.computerweekly.com/news/2240148820/BBC-wants-to-build-a-cultural-API|title=BBC wants to build a cultural API|work=[[ComputerWeekly.com]]|date=20 April 2012|accessdate=13 May 2012|first=Cliff|last=Saran|quote=an internal version of BBC iPlayer called Redux, which was originally developed for testing}}</ref><ref name="rose"/> which acts as a giant [[video on demand]] or [[personal video recorder]] (PVR).<ref name="butterworth">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/bbcinternet/2008/10/history_of_the_bbc_redux_proje.html|title=History of the 'BBC Redux' project|work=BBC Internet Blog|first=Brandon|last=Butterworth|date=27 October 2008|accessdate=12 May 2012}}</ref>  It contains a complete digital archive, recording both television and radio twenty-four hours a day, of all of the BBC's national and also some regional broadcast output since mid-2007,<ref name="tinley">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/researchanddevelopment/2011/11/abc-ip-and-work-on-audio-archi.shtml|title=ABC-IP and work on audio archiving research|first=Dominic|last=Tinley |date=8 November 2011|work=BBC Research & Development Blog}}</ref><ref name="tweed">{{cite web|url=http://metabroadcast.com/blog/introducing-tellytopic-navigating-programme-archives-by-topic|title=Introducing Tellytopic: Navigating programme archives by topic|work=MetaBroadcast|date=7 November 2011|accessdate=13 May 2012|first=Jonathan|last=Tweed|quote=BBC Redux, a playable archive of almost everything broadcast since mid-2007}}</ref> and is automatically compiled without human input.<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|5}}<ref name="rose"/> The BBC stated that BBC Redux is one of its major contributions to the field of digital archiving and preservation.<ref name="wright">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/researchanddevelopment/2010/06/the-value-of-everything.shtml|title=The Value of Everything|work=BBC Research & Development Blog|first=Richard|last=Wright|date=16 June 2010}}</ref>

Some accounts for accessing the system on a temporary basis were made available at Mashed&nbsp;08<ref name="johnson">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2008/jun/26/hacking.mashed08|title=Hackers fan the flames of imagination at Mashed|work=The Guardian|first=Bobbie|last=Johnson|date=26 June 2008|accessdate=13 May 2012}}</ref> and again at Culture Hack Day 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tumblr.iamdanw.com/post/2744690731/bbc-archive-a-number-of-redux-accounts-giving|title=BBC Archive − A number of Redux accounts giving…|first=Dan W.|last=Williams|work=Tumblr|date=14 January 2011}}</ref> providing streaming-only access to BBC content broadcast during the weekend of the event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://culturehackday.org.uk/wiki/Main/Datasets|title=Datasets|work=Culture Hack Day|date=14 January 2011}}</ref>  As well as streaming, the system enables high-quality downloads of television and radio content,<ref name="ebu">{{cite web|url=http://tech.ebu.ch/docs/events/p2p08/ebu_p2pseminar_08_programma_v3.pdf|title=Programme|conference=EBU Seminar on P2P delivery|location=Geneva|date=24 September 2008|accessdate=20 May 2012|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|quote=BBC Research developed a Redux site enabling a high quality download service of some BBC TV products.}}</ref> and has had the option to download subtitles from programmes since 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mashed08.backnetwork.com/event/?articleid=32|title=BBC Redux|department=Mashed 08|work=Backnetwork|publisher=Madgex|year=2008}}</ref>

BBC Redux had originally been developed at the BBC's Kingswood Warren campus,<ref name="forrester">{{cite web|url=http://cubicgarden.com/tag/kingswood/|title=Goodbye Kingswood warren|date=14 March 2011|work=Cubic Garden|first=Ian|last=Forrester}}</ref> in only two months,<ref name="singleton">{{cite journal|format=Platform-neutral content|work=[[Linux Format]]|title=Linux at the BBC|first=Alex|last=Singleton|url=http://diracvideo.org/download/press/LXF105.bbc_LPDF.pdf|origyear=13 March 2008|issue=105|date=May 2008|page=50|quote=Brandon Butterworth explains: 'People thought it would be really difficult to run on all platforms, that it would take years to develop. But I led a team to do a Flash version that would work on Linux and we did it in two months'}}</ref> and with the investment required being significantly less than the iPlayer.<ref name="rose"/> The saved content can be used for [[video logging|broadcast compliance checking]]<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|16}} and by BBC programme researchers.<ref name="annual-2009-2010">{{cite report|url=http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/rd/pubs/annual-review/bbc_rd_annual_review_2009-2010.pdf|title=Highlights of the Year|work=BBC R&D Annual Review 2009–2010|date=10 March 2011|accessdate=13 May 2012|page=4}}</ref>  {{As of|2012}}, BBC Redux is only available to employees, because existing legal contracts with content producers limit how material can be broadcast, distributed and made available to general consumers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/bbcinternet/2012/05/bbc_online_briefing_final_qa.html|title=BBC Online Briefing: Spring 2012 Final Q&A|work=BBC Internet Blog|first=Ralph|last=Rivera|date=11 May 2012|format=television question and answer session, offset 23:28–28:30}}</ref><ref name="tinworth"/> The [[README|Readme]] file for associated API frameworks hosted on [[GitHub]] states: {{quote|BBC Snippets and BBC Redux are tools designed to allow BBC staff to develop new ways to view and navigate content. As such, they're not open to the public.<ref name="haynes-readme">{{cite web|url=https://github.com/bbcsnippets/redux-client-ruby/blob/master/README.md|title=README.md|work=redux-client-ruby|publisher=GitHub|first=Matt|last=Haynes|date=25 January 2012|accessdate=13 May 2012}}</ref>}}

==Technical details==
The system records over 100&nbsp;megabits per second, continuously.<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|3}}  {{As of|2011|08}}, BBC Redux contained 300,000 hours of recorded audio and video.<ref name="davies">{{cite web|url=http://staff.science.uva.nl/~kamps/entertainme/presentations/04-Sam.pdf|title=BBC R&D – Archives Research|first1=Sam|last1=Davies|first2=Denise|last2=Bland|date=1 August 2011|accessdate=13 May 2012|page=4}}</ref>  Not all regional variations are recorded; for [[BBC One]], only London and Northern Ireland variants are recorded.<ref name="northwood">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cnorthwood/status/203178939525509120|first=Chris|last=Northwood|date=17 May 2012|accessdate=20 May 2012|title=Gah, Redux only records BBC One London;|work=@cnorthwood|publisher=Twitter}}</ref>

A series of standard Digital Video Broadcasting terrestrial antennas and satellite dishes, coupled to [[DVB-T]] and [[DVB-S]] [[TV tuner card]]s are used to capture the incoming [[multiplex (TV)|DVB multiplexes]]<ref name="tinworth">{{cite web|url=http://www.onemanandhisblog.com/archives/2012/04/the_uks_cultural_heritage_as_digital_pub.html|title=The UK's cultural heritage as digital public space|work=One Man and His Blog|first=Adam|last=Tinworth|date=20 April 2012|accessdate=13 May 2012|quote=BBC Redux is iPlayer on steroids – with an API. It records the whole digital multiplex, … But the rights are complicated- because the BBC doesn't own many of the programmes it broadcasts.}}</ref> transmitted for over-the-air [[Freesat]] and [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]] [[terrestrial television]].<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|5}}  These raw [[MPEG transport stream]]s are split into [[MPEG program stream|single-programme MPEG transport streams]], encapsulated in [[real-time Transport Protocol|RTP]], and sent using [[User Datagram Protocol|UDP]] [[IP multicast]] within the IPv4 [[multicast address]] range <code>233.122.227.0/24</code> from <code>[[autonomous system (Internet)|AS]]31459</code>.<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|5}}  From the multicast streams individual [[television programme]]s can be extracted and saved, without requiring any transcoding or conversion of the contained [[MPEG-2]] video data.<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|5}}

{{As of|2009|05}}, racks of [[Sun Fire]] T1000 and T2000 machines were used acquiring and storing the incoming programmes respectively; while commodity [[x86-64]] computers were used for database operations and playback transcoding.<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|4}}  The T2000 storage nodes are connected by [[10 Gigabit Ethernet]] on the network side,<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|7}} and then by [[serial attached SCSI]] to [[RAID]] boxes containing high-capacity [[commodity computing|commodity]] [[Serial ATA]] [[hard disk drive]]s.<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|7}}  The "[[fsck]]-free" [[ZFS]] [[file system]] is used after experiments with [[Unix File System]] (UFS) proved it to be too slow.<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|8}} [[Sun Microsystems]] had to manually repair the filesystems on two occasions using [[dd (Unix)|Unix <code>dd</code>]].<ref name="bird"/>{{rp|11–13}}

The software is based on [[Open-source software|open source]] technologies,<ref name="rose">{{cite journal|url=http://tech.ebu.ch/docs/techreview/trev_2008-Q4_iPlayer.pdf|title=Evolution of the BBC iPlayer|first=Anthony|last=Rose|authorlink=Anthony Rose (technology)|editor-first=F.|editor-last=Kozamernik|work=EBU Technical Review|year=2008|issue=Q4|page=2|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|accessdate=13 May 2012}};<br /> {{cite journal|url=http://tech.ebu.ch/docs/techreview/trev_bestof08.pdf|title=Evolution of the BBC iPlayer|first=Anthony|last=Rose|authorlink=Anthony Rose (technology)|editor-first=F.|editor-last=Kozamernik|work=EBU Technical Review|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|issue=The Best of 2008|page=5|date=24 February 2009|accessdate=13 May 2012}}</ref> and uses a combination of <code>[[mod_perl]]</code> and [[C (programming language)|C]] running on [[OpenSolaris]].<ref name="bird">{{cite paper|url=http://www.uknof.org.uk/uknof13/Bird-Redux.pdf|first=Tom|last=Bird|date=28 May 2009|title=BBC Redux|publisher=[[UKNOF]] 13|location=Sheffield|pages=2–16}}</ref>{{rp|9,14}}  A series of "[[lolcat]]" images are used for the system's [[HTTP 404]] and error pages.<ref name="edent">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/edent/status/119776630569836546/photo/1|title=I do like the BBC Redux 404 page|first=Terence|last=Eden|work=@edent|publisher=Twitter|date=30 September 2011}}</ref>

==Projects==
As part of the European Union (EU) "NoTube" project running between 2009–12. a recommendation research system using [[Lonclass]] categorisation and [[Jaccard index#Tanimoto Similarity and Distance|Tanimoto coefficient]] matching was tested by the BBC R&D Audience Experience team and integrated with 23,000 recordings delivered from Redux.<ref name="notube">{{cite web|url=http://labs.notu.be/1/bbc/about.html|title=NoTube Archive Browser Experiment 1|work=NoTube Archive Browser|date=19 December 2011|accessdate=13 May 2012}}</ref>  The matching dataset was gathered over a period of five months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://notube.tv/2011/10/14/algorithms-for-recommendations-in-various-n-screen-implementations/|title=Algorithms for recommendations in various N-Screen implementations|first=Libby|last=Miller|work=NoTube|date=14 October 2011|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref>

For a BBC Digital Media Initiative (DMI) demonstration entitled "Million Minutes", files from the BBC's [[D-3 (video)|D-3 video tape]] archive were imported into the Redux system during 2009–2010.<ref name="annual-2009-2010"/>   This also used commercial software from [[Artesia Digital Media Group]] and involved creating a [[representational state transfer]] (REST) interface onto the content stored within Redux.<ref name="james-archak">{{cite web|url=http://custard-cat.blogspot.co.uk/2009/11/archak-bbc-research-and-development.html|title=ArcHak|work=CustardCat|first=Bruce|last=James|date=5 November 2009|accessdate=13 May 2012}}</ref>

During 2010, [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]]<ref name="starling">{{cite web|url=https://github.com/whomwah/Redux-Switcher/blob/master/README.md|title=README.md|work=Safari-Redux-Switcher|publisher=GitHub|date=4 September 2011|accessdate=15 May 2012|first=Sam|last=Starling}}</ref> and [[Google Chrome]]<ref name="robertson">{{cite web|url=https://github.com/whomwah/Redux-Switcher/blob/master/README.md|title=README.md|work=Redux Switcher|publisher=GitHub|first=Duncan|last=Robertson|date=26 August 2010|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref> [[browser extension]]s were developed to integrate Redux content with the main [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes www.bbc.co.uk/programmes] directory.<ref name="browser-extensions">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/researchanddevelopment/2010/08/-prototyping-weeknotes-29-2708.shtml|title=Prototyping Weeknotes #29|date=27 August 2010|accessdate=13 May 2012|work=BBC Research & Development Blog}}</ref>

In January 2012, the BBC's Multimedia Classification team announced they were hoping to test and add "mood-based navigation" to the existing BBC Redux interface,<ref name="dtg">{{cite web|url=http://www.dtg.org.uk/news/news.php?id=4296|title=BBC R&D develops 'mood based navigation'|work=News|publisher=[[Digital TV Group]]|author=DTG Staff|date=18 January 2012}}</ref><ref name="campbell">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/researchanddevelopment/2012/01/an-interface-for-mood-based-navigation.shtml|title=An Affective Interface for Mood-Based Navigation|first=Rosie|last=Campbell|date=16 January 2012|accessdate=13 May 2012|work=BBC Research & Development Blog}}</ref><ref name="redux-mood-testing">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/rd/projects/2009/10/mulitmedia_classification.shtml|work=Projects|title=Multimedia Classification|author=BBC Research and Development|accessdate=13 May 2012|quote=User Evaluation on BBC Redux (by BBC staff) …}}</ref> along with [[audience measurement]] and other rich [[metadata]] comprising work part-funded by the [[Technology Strategy Board]].<ref name="tinley"/>    During 2010–2011 BBC Research and Development integrated content archived in BBC Redux with the BBC's existing internal BBC [[Infax|InFax]] system, allowing finding of metadata and archive content within the same browser window,<ref>{{cite report|title=Highlights of the Year|work=BBC R&D Annual Report 2010–2011|url=http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/rd/pubs/annual-review/bbc_rd_annual_review_2010-2011.pdf|page=5|date=15 November 2011}}</ref> covering news and [[subtitle (captioning)|subtitles]] from over the previous five years.<ref name="mcathy">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.journalism.co.uk/2012/04/20/odcc-open-data-and-the-new-digital-fields-of-exchange/|title=#ODCC – Open data and the 'new digital fields of exchange'|first=Rachel|last=McAthy|date=20 April 2012|work=Journalism.co.uk|publisher=Mousetrap Media Ltd}}</ref>

During March 2012, the Atlas index changed the method of equivalence matching used for indexing against BBC Redux.<ref name="tweed-equivalence">{{cite web|url=http://metabroadcast.com/blog/atlas-release-notes-week-to-20th-mar|title=Atlas release notes - week to 20th March |work=MetaBroadcast|date=21 March 2012|accessdate=15 May 2012|first=Jonathan|last=Tweed|quote=Changes to the behaviour of BBC Redux equivalence}}</ref>

