The '''Caxton Society''' was founded in the United Kingdom in 1845 to promote the publication of inexpensive and convenient editions of [[Middle Ages|medieval]] literature, including [[chronicle]]s, that had not yet appeared in print.{{sfn|Heylin|1851}}<ref name=BndF>{{cite web|url=http://data.bnf.fr/fr/16938635/caxton_society_gb/ |title=Caxton Society. GB |publisher=[[Bibliothèque nationale de France]] |date=5 October 2018 |language=French |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116145132/http://data.bnf.fr/fr/16938635/caxton_society_gb/ |deadurl=no |archivedate=16 November 2018 |accessdate=16 November 2018 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was named after [[William Caxton]], and listed thirty-three founding members, among whom were [[Samuel Wilberforce]], [[List of bishops of Oxford|Bishop of Oxford]], [[Merton College Library|Merton College Library, Oxford]], the [[Francis Palgrave|Deputy Keeper of the Public Record Office]], the then president of [[Trinity College, Oxford]], the library of the [[Society of Writers to Her Majesty's Signet|Writers to the Signet]] and the [[antiquarian]] [[Thomas Wright (antiquarian)|Thomas Wright]].{{sfn|Levine|1986|pp=50, 179}}{{sfn|Heylin|1851}}{{refn|[[Philippa Levine]] cites Bishop [[Samuel Wilberforce]] of Oxford, a leading critic of [[Charles Darwin]]'s work towards a theory of [[evolution]], to exemplify a belief that supporting endeavours such as the Caxton Society advanced a "[[Divine providence|Providential plan]]": in a speech given in 1857, "he declared that 'there was far more than the mere gratification of a somewhat idle curiosity when archaeologists ransacked the dust of antiquity. They were carrying out the great plan of the Creator and Ruler of the world.' History was invested with divine intention."{{sfn|Levine|1986|p=56}}|group=Fn}} Members did not pay a subscription, but were required to buy at least one publication: these were funded by income from sales.{{sfn|Heylin|1851}} The Society ceased operating in 1854, by which time it had published at least 15&nbsp;volumes.<ref name=BndF /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://royalhistsoc.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/caxtonsociety.pdf |title=Caxton Society |publisher=[[Royal Historical Society]] |date=n.d. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116145723/https://royalhistsoc.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/caxtonsociety.pdf |deadurl=no |archivedate=16 November 2018 |accessdate=16 November 2018 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{refn|While Levine does not reference the failure of the Caxton Society directly, she observes that, in the 19th century, "[t]here were numerous&nbsp;... cases of [similar] societies which, after a few volumes, simply ceased publishing. It was not a lack of demand that led to these failures nor a saturation of the market, [but rather the] aims [of these societies] were too much akin to those of the Camden Society whose early successes had established its supremacy in the field."{{sfn|Levine|1986|p=66}}|group=Fn}}

