{{Infobox Court Case | name = JT Stratford & Son Ltd v Lindley | court = [[Court of Appeal]] | image = | caption = | date decided = | full name = | citations = [1965] AC 269 | judges = [[James Reid, Baron Reid|Lord Reid]] | prior actions = | subsequent actions = | opinions = | transcripts = | keywords = [[Right to strike]], common law, [[fundamental right]] }} '''''JT Stratford & Son Ltd v Lindley''''' [1965] AC 269 is a [[UK labour law]] case that concerns [[economic tort]] and strike action.
==Facts== The union embargoed JT Stratford & Son, the parent company of a subsidiary that the union was in dispute with. They refused to handle the barges of JT Stratford.
==Judgment== The House of Lords held
Lord Reid said the following.<ref>[1965] AC 269, 324</ref>
{{quote|The respondents' action made it practically impossible for the appellants to do any new business with the barge hirers.}}
It was not disputed that such interference is tortious if any unlawful means are employed.
